20 minutes away, the other is 45 minutes away. There is no way I am letting her travel in a taxi for an hour and a half per day and that's in good conditions. &#10;On the other hand I don't want her going into a mainstream class with no support, she attended a mainstream nursery who just didn't know how to help her. She is currently in an early years assessment unit but has to leave here due to her age. SInce she has been in the unit she has come on in leaps and bounds. It is like someone has flicked a switch in her and suddenly she is able to join in with the rest of us. &#10;Sorry for waffling on with no advice, just wanted you to know that you are not alone"/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="967" language="en" documentId="4944" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Vicky T(51)" date="29-03-10 23:35" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://www.netmums.com/coffeehouse/netmums-coffeehouse-archives-528/primary-school-admission-appeals-clinic-599/404307-special-educational-needs-re-mainstream-school-all.html" topic="mainstreaming" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="4944" notes="" title="Special Educational Needs re. Mainstream school"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="466"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="467" end="882"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="883" end="967"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>